text: <@U08GFT5V5> <@U061HDV96> anyone want to critique a WIP language syntax?
<@U061HDV96> in particular since it's sort of Pythonic
Sure
<@U053LEHJN> I will shred your language
I will leave nothing in its wake
I will Pythonise your language
rough example of hello world:
I wanted to see how feasible a language without using characters not on the Pixel C's keyboard would be
that means no curly braces or square brackets
I think the use of brackets is excessive
and I guess that `print` could actually be without the parentheses
`import` might be preceded with `@` too
If you want it to be Pythonic, then there shouldn't be any brackets at all
<@U061HDV96> no, I meant Python without the stupidness
significant whitespace is awful
/gif triggered

```
@module "hello"

@import: 
  std.io.print
  std.lang.array
  std.lang.string

main (args: array of string ) do
  println "Hello, World!"
end
```
Is print a function or a reserved word?

>significant whitespace is awful

wooord
function
I hate the do end <@U08GFT5V5>
Useless
`@` prefixed stuff is more like compiler commands
obviously
<@U08GFT5V5> nah eddie’s first one is better
"annotations"
<@U08GFT5V5> I use the colons so that the language can easily be used as a description format
<@U0548MM6B> It looks a lot like go
The -> is unneeded imo
`key: value`
<@U061HDV96> the `->` tells the compiler that it's transforming one list to another
Here is my rationale… you can disagree
i.e. a function is just something that transforms a list of arguments into a list of expressions
<@U053LEHJN> wut?
You should use an arrow for a return value type or something
return types are inferred
but they can be explicit if need be
And you can make them explicit with the arrow

I felt that he was going for something super high level, more descriptive and less pragmatic like python. because of this it’s natural to have significant whitespace. It takes up less space and as a result likes to do more in less code.
<@U053LEHJN> it only makes sense to have lamdas everywhere if you want to make a functional first language
not great for general purpose syntax

```
addNums: (x: i32, y: i32) -> i32
(
  x + y
)
```
then how do you deal with order of operations?
example?
<@U053LEHJN> it also infers the return?
<@U061HDV96> naturally
It assumes the last line is a return?
yes
Can you force a return?
I don't see why not
<@U061HDV96> he hasn’t made the lang yet
<@U08GFT5V5> I know
we are just theorizing
I'm just asking questions of what he has made up in his mind
<@U08GFT5V5> I'm not seeing the order of operations issue
Honestly, I hate the ()
It's so unneeded
You will end up with something like clojure
Or I just hate the fact that you put them on their own lines
<@U061HDV96> that's just style, lol

```
addNums: (x: i32, y: i32) -> i32 (
  x + y
)
```
you can do it that way if you want
You know
the addNums:

```
addNums: (x: i32, y: i32) -> i32 (x + y)
```
It reminds me of JS
or that
<@U061HDV96> like I said, this should have a description syntax built-in
to replace JSON
<@U053LEHJN> ^ my case
^ That looks very confusing
PEMDAS?
order of operations isn't an issue
<@U053LEHJN> maybe I described it poorly. I can’t tell where anything starts or stops
I'll use that same order that mathematics uses
heh
with `{ }` you know it’s always a block
syntax highlighting?
<@U08GFT5V5> I mostly agree, but I wanted to try without {}/[]
when you have `( )` everywhere it’s basically clojure like
() is all that's available on the Pixel C keyboard without using shortcuts
<@U08GFT5V5> and you mean Lisp, and I agree :slightly_smiling_face:
I say ditch it for significant spacing
though my goal is Lisp with _less_ parentheses
like, parentheses surrounding EVERYTHING is too much
or make it optional
<@U08GFT5V5> but the basic idea is that code is data
either spaces or `( )`
so you have lists of data/lists of expressions
well it’s an idea
Might be worth throwing together a quick interpreter to see how it feels
<@U08GFT5V5> yeah
<@U08GFT5V5> I want to start with a protobuf/flatbuffer alternative first
hence my data-description goal

might be wrong
<@U053LEHJN> do you want to help improve kotlin as a language?
There’s a construct i’ve always wanted in a lang
Junctions
where you do something like this

should work as 

```
if( a == "val" || a == "val2" || a == "val3") { … }
```

I don’t think I would want to read that first one, I get where you are going with that but the syntax is confusing. I like the idea and it may be better if it had a different symbol to convey what is happening
the use of `||` would give me pause while `,` would just logically, to me, mean this is some kind of `inArray` check
<@U08GFT5V5> that's a parsing ambiguity
you'd need to wrap the right-hand side in ()
true
perl’s done it already
their syntax
also if you wrap it, then you're comparing `a` to a `boolean` technically
<@U08GFT5V5> Kotlin has `when`
and sorta-pattern-matching
Well the idea is not to do one kind of equality check
hmm… actually it is

what I had in mind

```
if a is equal to val or val2 or val3
```

but it could just as easily be 

```
if a is equal to val and val2 or val3
```
maybe not too sensible… but you get the idea
<@U08GFT5V5> what Kotlin does have is `in`
so you could do:

they'd consider bringing them back but they want good use cases
